Pub Date: March 5th

Thanks to @netgalley and @macmillanaudio for the audiobook! 

Synopsis: In 1985, Anita de Monte was poised to take the art world by storm until her untimely death seemingly erased her art from history.  In present day, art student Raquel stumbles upon Anitaâ€™s work during research for her thesis and begins to uncover what really happened to end Anitaâ€™s life. 

Thoughts: This is such a unique book! Told in two parallel timelines following artist Anita de Monte in 1985 and art student Raquel in the present day, both womenâ€™s stories examine what it is to have power and who has the right to leave a legacy. Themes of race, class, gender, and art are central to this book.  Several genres were blended together to make for a very interesting read.  I enjoyed both timelines and both womenâ€™s povs (the male pov was necessary to the story but less enjoyable). The murder mystery aspect of the story was well done, and I liked that the timelines tied together, but it took quite awhile to get to the point where they connected.  A note on the audio: SO GOOD! The narrators packed so much personality into the characters and did an excellent job. Highly recommend checking this book out on audio if you get the chance!

This is my first book by this author, but I do own â€œOlga Dies Dreamingâ€, which has now been bumped up on my tbr. 

I read this book over the course of a few days, and will say it started off slow for me. However, when I say â€œslowâ€ I donâ€™t mean it in a bad way. More in, it took a little time to figure out the direction the book was moving in, and to become fully invested. Once I did though I was hooked! 

I find the authorâ€™s writing to be both exquisite and very well-written. I loved how the 2 stories of Anita and Raquel paralleled one another. They are both Latina female artists trying to be seen in a â€œmanâ€™s worldâ€, - to make a name for themselves without the help of their partners. 

I listened to this on audio and I must say that the narrators did a fantastic job!

Jessica Pimentel in particular did such a fascinating job with Anita. She really captured and delivered the character, which is described as only 5ft tall and small, but with a larger than life attitude.

I enjoyed the blending of historical fiction, art history, and pop culture (that Iâ€™m familiar with and grew up with). 

What I loved most about this book, aside from the writing, is finding myself comparing the lives of Anita and Raquel. Seeing some similarities but also recognizing the differences. The multiple POVs were done well even Jacks. 

XÃ³chitl is a great storyteller, and this book is one Iâ€™d describe as a comfort read. A story filled with passion, despair, revenge from beyond the grave, and courage, you wonâ€™t be disappointed when reading this.

text:
Xochitl Gonzalezâ€™s debut, OLGA DIES DREAMING, hits everything I love in a â€œtreatâ€ book: fun but not frivolous, smart but not pretentious, seriously considered but not overly heavy. In her sophomore novel, ANITA DE MONTE LAUGHS LAST (out today!), Gonzalez channels her signature style onto a different landscape, and I enjoyed it every bit as much.
 
In the historical timeline, itâ€™s the 1980s, and Anita de Monte is a rising artist married to Jack Martin, a famous sculptor, but their relationship is marred by misogyny, art world power dynamics, and infidelity. When Anita decides sheâ€™s had enough, things turn more dire than she could have imagined. Meanwhile, in the modern-day timeline, Raquel is an undergrad at Brown who plans to study Jack Martinâ€™s work for her art history thesis. Her summer internship at RISD finds her unearthing long-buried facts about Martinâ€¦and some new realizations about her own high-society boyfriend.
 
Gonzalez concocts the perfect elixir of propulsive plot, larger-than-life characters, honest self-discovery, blazingly fun writing, and a delicious revenge storyline (with a touch of the supernatural) that makes this an unforgettable story. Itâ€™s fresh, enjoyable, unapologetic, and satisfying. My one minor quibble is thereâ€™s some fat shaming of the villain that felt unnecessary.
 
Thereâ€™s this amazing speech near the end that gave me the chills: â€œDid the school just let me in to fill a quota and make everyone feel better for being so open-minded? Am I supposed to just churn out the same thoughts as everyone else? To worship the same gods you did? Iâ€™m told time and again that my culture, my background, arenâ€™t worthy of study or time. Was I supposed to come here and pretend to have had the same life you did? Parrot the same opinions? The same perspectives? Or am I here to fucking change things?â€ ğŸ”¥
 
Donâ€™t sleep on the audio version; the narrating team of Jessica Pimental, Stacy Gonzalez, and Jonathan Gregg is exceptional. Thank you @flatiron_books @macmillan.audio @netgalley for the ARC and ALC.

Thank you for the gifted copy of Victim by Andrew Boryga, Doubleday Books! I love the bookmark too.

Yâ€™all, this is one of my highly anticipated books -and debuts- of 2024! I know I say that for almost every book I post here, but I swear, itâ€™s especially true this time. The synopsis is right up my alley, take a look and let me know if youâ€™re intrigued as well.

Publisherâ€™s Summary:
Thereâ€™s a fine line between bending the truth and telling bold-faced lies, and Javier Perez is willing to cross it. Victim is a fearless satire about a hustler from the Bronx who sees through the veneer of diversity initiatives and decides to cash in on the odd currency of identity.

Javier Perez is a hustler from a family of hustlers. He learns from an early age how to play the game to his own advantage, how his backgroundâ€”murdered drug dealer dad, single cash-strapped mom, best friend serving time for gang activityâ€”can be a key to doors he didnâ€™t even know existed. This kind of story, molded in the right way, is just what college admissions committees are looking for, and a full academic scholarship to a prestigious university brings Javi one step closer to his dream of becoming a famous writer.

As a college student, Javi embellishes his life story until thereâ€™s not even a kernel of truth left. The only real connection to his past is the occasional letter he trades with his childhood best friend, Gio, who doesnâ€™t seem to care about Javiâ€™s newfound awareness of white privilege or the school-to-prison pipeline. Soon after Javi graduates, a viral essay transforms him from a writer on the rise to a journalist at a legendary magazine where the editors applaud his â€œunique perspective.â€ But Gio more than anyone knows who Javi really is, and sees through his game. Once Gioâ€™s released from prison and Javi offers to cut him in on the deal, will he play along with Javiâ€™s charade, or will it all come crumbling down?

A sendup of virtue signaling and tear-jerking trauma plots written with the bite of Paul Beatty, Victim asks what real diversity looks like and how far one man is willing to go to make his story hit the right notes.

Side Table Exit Survey :: #AnitaDeMonteLaughsLast by Xochitl Gonzalez (#gifted @flatiron_books)
ğŸ–¼ï¸
READ IF YOU LIKE...
â€¢ The world of art
â€¢ Calling out microaggressions in prominently white spaces
â€¢ Justice
ğŸ–¼ï¸
I THOUGHT IT WAS...
A brilliant, smart, and vibrant novel that honors the creativity and artwork of people of color, women especially. Anita de Monte is an artist on the rise in 1985, fighting not to be overshadowed by her famous white husband, when her life and career are cut short. Raquel is an art history major at Brown in 1998, trying to find her way in an institution and field dominated by rich whiteness, when she's swept up in a passionate relationship with a hot-shot senior artist.

ANITA does for the art world what DISORIENTATION did for academia -- it confronts the racism, white privilege, sexism, and false allyship rampant in the field and ruthlessly calls it out through a dynamic and gripping story. It scrutinizes why white artists are lauded, studied, and taught to future generations while artists of color are often excluded from the conversation. It also examines how white men tend to blindly uphold other white men, conveniently and problematically excluding pieces of narrative that call character into question.

But you don't have to have a passion for the art world to enjoy this, because this novel is also about relationships, the ones that make you stronger and the ones that tear you down without you even realizing it. Gonzalez has written a reminder to all women to never invest energy in insecurity and never let a partner make you feel less-than. We've worked hard for the space we've claimed, so we're not going to believe when we're told we probably shouldn't sit at the table, however politely it's implied.

Review: ANITA DE MONTE LAUGHS LAST by Xochitl Gonzalez
Pub date: 3.5.24 

When an artist dies, who gets to tell their story? 

This question is not new. Really, who gets to tell the â€œcorrectâ€ version of any story or history for that matter? It feels that history is always skewed to show the version of the ones who â€œwonâ€ - the majority, or those who lived on. 

Have you heard of Ana Mendieta? I wouldnâ€™t be surprised if you havenâ€™t. I had never heard of her until I read this novel. Mendieta was a Cuban American artist in the 80â€™s who died after falling down from the 34th floor of her NYC apartment. Or was she pushed? The prime suspect was her husband â€”minimalist sculptor Carl Andre. He was acquitted of her murder after a trial and went on with his art career with impunity while Mendietaâ€™s art was largely forgotten. 

ANITA is in part, an homage to Mendieta, recasting Mendieta as Anita, and her husband as white, art-darling Jack Martin. Gonzalez knits together two stories, decades apart, and draws parallels between the experiences of two Latinx women: the story of Anita in the 80â€™s NYC art scene and the story of Puerto Rican student Raquel Torres who moves away from Brooklyn to attend a New England college in the 90â€™s. Torres is influenced by her white professor to write her thesis on Jack Martin. Raquel stumbles upon the story of Anita de Monte and uncovers a life and art, marginalized by a larger community. 

Anita and Raquelsâ€™ lives are intertwined in many ways, with both women battling for validity in the predominantly-white spaces of art and academia. And both women are affected in different ways by their white partners. Anitaâ€™s chapters are perfection. I love how the author conveyed Raquelâ€™s insecurities. In many ways, I felt like Raquel. We both went to mostly-white colleges at around that same time. And when you feel like a fish out of water, you start to question yourself, your identity, and what you want in life, trying to balance it all. Damn, that scene with those bitches (IYKYK). 

Folks, you are in for a treat. IG will not allow me to write more, so please read the comments for the continuation.

â“What was the last new release that you read?â£
â£
One of my recent reads was Anita de Monte Laughs Last by Xochitl Gonzalez (thank you @flatirons_books & @macmillan.audio for my gifted copy), which is now available!â£
â£
This story unfolds in dual timelines. One timeline (1985) follows Anita de Monte, a rising star in the art world whose life meets a tragic and unjust end. The other timeline (1998) follows Raquel, a brown art student in a sea of white who learns of Anitaâ€™s story, which mirrors so much of her own.â£
â£
Donâ€™t let this character driven plot fool you, I flew through these pages as I was desperate to find out more about Anita and her rage that was palpable from start to finish. â£
â£
Anita is an incredible character, and I wanted to burn down the world for her. Her passion is infectious, and I love that Gonzalez doesnâ€™t care whether the audience loves her or not. Raquel is the antithesis of Anita at first, but when she really dives into the injustice of Anitaâ€™s story, she becomes an absolute force in her own right. â£
â£
Gonzalez does an incredible job of examining the question of who gets to have their stories glorified in history versus who gets left behindâ€¦and of course, you know which side the upper echelon will always choose. â£
â£
While this book may want you to scream and throw things, itâ€™s impeccably written and worth the emotions. â£

Anita De Monte Laughs Last
Xochitl Gonzalez

1985. Anita de Monte, a rising star in the art world, is found dead in New York City; her tragic death is the talk of the town. Until it isnâ€™t. By 1998 Anitaâ€™s name has been all but forgottenâ€”certainly by the time Raquel, a third-year art history student is preparing her final thesis. On College Hill, surrounded by privileged students whose futures are already paved out for them, Raquel feels like an outsider. Students of color, like her, are the minority there, and the pressure to work twice as hard for the same opportunities is no secret.

But when Raquel becomes romantically involved with a well-connected older art student, she finds herself unexpectedly rising up the social ranks. As she attempts to straddle both worlds, she stumbles upon Anitaâ€™s story, raising questions about the dynamics of her own relationship, which eerily mirrors that of the forgotten artist.

Moving back and forth through time and told from the perspectives of both women, Anita de Monte Laughs Last is a propulsive, witty examination of power, love, and art, daring to ask who gets to be remembered and who is left behind in the rarefied world of the elite.

Anticipated Releases - March 2024

March is another stellar month for new releases! At a glance, a few are from favourite authors and a few are from new-to-me authors, some titles caught my attention while others it was the cover art. It's also a month for some great Canadian content. 

And of course, my most anticipated release of the entire year - Here After by the incredibly talented @literaryamy. I read through this debut memoir in one sitting and then immediately started it over again. Amy has put into words so many things I have struggled to articulate in my own grief. It is real, it is raw, it is painful, and it is absolutely beautiful. Kurtis was absolutely right - she is a gift to the literary world. Here After will easily be my favourite book of the entire year. Do yourself a favour and read it.

This Could Be Us lived up to my expectations (scroll back for my full review), I will be starting The Inheritance this weekend, and eagerly awaiting my preorder of Expiration Dates to arrive this week.

Let me know in the comments what is/was your most anticipated March release? Or what has been your favourite March release you've read?

New in: Reese's Book Club's latest pick!

Who gets to leave a legacy?

1985. Anita de Monte, a rising star in the art world, is found dead in New York City; her tragic death is the talk of the town. Until it isnâ€™t. By 1998 Anitaâ€™s name has been all but forgotten â€“ certainly by the time Raquel, a third-year art history student is preparing her final thesis. On College Hill, surrounded by progeny of film producers, C-Suite executives, and international art-dealers, most of whom float through life knowing that their futures are secured, Raquel feels herself an outsider. Students of colour, like Raquel, are the minority there, and the pressure to work twice as hard for the same opportunities is no secret.

But when Raquel becomes romantically involved with a well-connected older art student, she finds herself unexpectedly rising up the social ranks. As she attempts to straddle both worlds, she stumbles upon Anitaâ€™s story, raising questions about the dynamics of her own relationship, which eerily mirrors that of the forgotten artist.

Moving back and forth through time and told from the perspectives of both women, Anita de Monte Laughs Last is a propulsive, witty examination of power, love and art, daring to ask who gets to be remembered and who is left behind in the rarefied world of the elite.

Anita De Monte Laughs Last, an amazing story by @xochitltheg!

âœ¨Synopsisâœ¨
New York Times bestselling author Xochitl Gonzalez delivers a mesmerizing novel about a first-generation Ivy League student who uncovers the genius work of a female artist decades after her suspicious death

1985. Anita de Monte, a rising star in the art world, is found dead in New York City; her tragic death is the talk of the town. Until it isnâ€™t. By 1998 Anitaâ€™s name has been all but forgottenâ€”certainly by the time Raquel, a third-year art history student is preparing her final thesis. On College Hill, surrounded by privileged students whose futures are already paved out for them, Raquel feels like an outsider. Students of color, like her, are the minority there, and the pressure to work twice as hard for the same opportunities is no secret.

But when Raquel becomes romantically involved with a well-connected older art student, she finds herself unexpectedly rising up the social ranks. As she attempts to straddle both worlds, she stumbles upon Anitaâ€™s story, raising questions about the dynamics of her own relationship, which eerily mirrors that of the forgotten artist.

âœ¨My Mini Reviewâœ¨

I have always loved art museums, reading and learning about art, and am an art therapist so I was very excited to read this story. 

This story is told in dual timelines and from different points of view and I really enjoyed that. I found Anita and Raquel to both be strong women yearning for identity and acceptance. 

The story was written very well with a complex and thoughtful storyline that really was incredibly engaging. I donâ€™t know who doesnâ€™t love a revenge story! 

4 â­ï¸

Huge thank you to @booksparks and @xochitltheg for my early copy

Anita De Monte Laughs Last  Author: Xochitl Gonzalez @xochitltheg 
Publisher: @flatiron_books , @macmillan.audio 
Pages: 342  Hours: 13.5

â€œNew York Times bestselling author Xochitl Gonzalez delivers a mesmerizing novel about a first-generation Ivy League student who uncovers the genius work of a female artist decades after her suspicious death.

Moving back and forth through time and told from the perspectives of both women, Anita de Monte Laughs Last is a propulsive, witty examination of power, love, and art, daring to ask who gets to be remembered and who is left behind in the rarefied world of the elite.â€

My thoughts:
This book embraces the intersectionality of ethnicity and race and gender in the art world, highlighting themes I admittedly did not consider before but really wish I had thought more about. 

Parallel themes on women and the patriarchy, ethnicity, power, creativity, wealth, and the connected stories become more woven together in powerful ways that amplify how whiteness and wealth underlie a lot of the art world and then what trickles down into other spaces, including colleges and educational spaces.  There were some scenes with Raque that resonated with me, made me slow down and think about underrepresented and first generation students where I work, how they are seen, treated, and (un)supported in both visible and invisible ways.

Within all of these themes is a bad*ss revenge story.  This was a hugely satisfying and important read for me and the audiobook is an amazing way to experience this book, especially the performance for Anita De Monteâ€™s character. 

Q: last book that wowed you?  If you could haunt someone as a form of revengeâ€¦ what would you do?

ANITA DE MONTE is a novel about a first generation art history student uncovering the work of a Cuban artist whose art has been all but forgotten following her suspicious death. Told from three perspectives, Gonzalez is a story about gatekeeping in art and a story of reclamation for both Anita and Raquel, the third year art history student who uncovers Anitaâ€™s story. I loved Anitaâ€™s spirit and found myself searching the internet for art from the Cuban feminist artist whose biography seems to be an inspiration, Ana Mendieta. I included one of my favorite pieces from Mendieta above. As I read, I couldnâ€™t help but think about gatekeeping in publishing and what literature is deemed most notable or worthy of praise and big marketing budgets.

By 1998 Anitaâ€™s name has been all but forgottenâ€”certainly by the time Raquel, a third-year art history student is preparing her final thesis. Students of color, like her, are the minority there, and the pressure to work twice as hard for the same opportunities is no secret.

But when Raquel becomes romantically involved with a well-connected older art student, she finds herself unexpectedly rising up the social ranks. Moving back and forth through time and told from the perspectives of both women, Anita de Monte Laughs Last examines power, love, and art, asking who gets to be remembered and who is left behind in the rarefied world of the elite.

â­ï¸ Book Review â­

Anita De Monte Laughs Last
Author: Xochitl Gonzalez

Book Rating â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸

This is Reeseâ€™s Book Clubâ€™s March pick. I had read Gonzalezâ€™s debut, Olga Dies Dreaming and I really enjoyed it so I was excited to dive into her latest.

This is an odd book. The synopsis is a bit misleading. It says that an Ivy League student uncovers the genius work of a female artist decades after her suspicious death in 1985. Yes that does happen but in the last quarter of the book.

It alternates between the artist, Anita who is very much alive and the student, Raquel. They are ENTIRELY separate stories until Raquel learns about Anita at the end of the book. I was a little annoyed with it because I was patiently waiting for the stories to converge.

The Anita story is more engaging, first itâ€™s set in the â€˜80s, yeah! She is a BIPOC artist married to Jack, a famous white minimalist artist.There is so much passion and intensity in this relationship and its writing. Thereâ€™s racial and artistic commentary as well as good old jealousy. There are Jack chapters, but he is written so flat and one-note that they take you out of the story.

Raquel is a young BIPOC artist who is also dating a white dude in the present. Her chapters read YA and like a totally different book. She is studying Jackâ€™s work and very slowly learns about Anita and the white controlled art world.

There is kind of a murder mystery?? I wouldâ€™ve much preferred if Raquel learned about Anita early on and solved her murder. This book lacks pace and plot, BUT the Anita chapters are gems. 

#QOTD - When reading a dual POV, do you find you like one more than the other?

Thanks to @booksparks for having me on their #WRC2024! Anita De Monte Laughs Last is my last book to share. You have probably been seeing this one all over. Itâ€™s getting excellent reviews. Itâ€™s definitely one of the most anticipated books of the year! 

What is one of your most anticipated books this year? 

1985. Anita de Monte, a rising star in the art world, is found dead in New York City; her tragic death is the talk of the town. Until it isnâ€™t. By 1998 Anitaâ€™s name has been all but forgottenâ€•certainly by the time Raquel, a third-year art history student is preparing her final thesis. On College Hill, surrounded by privileged students whose futures are already paved out for them, Raquel feels like an outsider. Students of color, like her, are the minority there, and the pressure to work twice as hard for the same opportunities is no secret. â€¨â€¨But when Raquel becomes romantically involved with a well-connected older art student, she finds herself unexpectedly rising up the social ranks. As she attempts to straddle both worlds, she stumbles upon Anitaâ€™s story, raising questions about the dynamics of her own relationship, which eerily mirrors that of the forgotten artist.â€¨â€¨Moving back and forth through time and told from the perspectives of both women, Anita de Monte Laughs Last is a propulsive, witty examination of power, love, and art, daring to ask who gets to be remembered and who is left behind in the rarefied world of the elite.

Raquel is an art history student at Brown trying to find her way into the cliquish (and very white) posh students there and seems to be driven into the art space of Jack Martin, who she is planning on doing her thesis about. Delving into the past, Anita Del Monte, is a successful artist of her own right, married to Jack Martin but never being given the dues she deserved, and when she is tragically killed, her husband, rather than honoring her, wants to squash her former glory and art. Raquel upon realizing this legacy, finds commonalities with Anita as she tries to make space for herself in her passions and refuses to be put down by other, extraneous voices and so called friends. The first half of this was a struggle for me. I enjoyed the Raquel parts more than the Anita stuff. I found her more realistic and relatable. But Anita narration was a slog. The second half ties together more neatly and I appreciate the way the two perspective complemented each other. It's an interesting read and definitely has some important points of focus. â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸1/2

Anita De Monte Laughs Last is a moving, visceral, and ultimately hopeful work. This work centers two  powerful Latina women  Anita De Monte and Raquel Toro separated by time, but connected through art and their shared experiences of love and betrayal, both women are unwilling to be used as pawns. This work centers art, finding yourself, and dealing with being seen as an outsider and interloper. I highly recommend this work and found it as a Chicana incredibly moving and relatable, in particularly grappling with cultural assimilation, and how this is pushed upon both Anita and Raquel.

A page-turner, dual timeline, and full of art history. In 1985, Anita de Monte, a rising star in the art world, is found dead in New York City. Her name is forgotten until 1998 when Raquel, stumbles upon Anitaâ€™s story when writing her final thesis. Their stories mirror each other as both women navigate the art world of the elite. Also, the story is based off of the real artist Ana Mendieta who died in September 1985 in a fall from a 34th-floor and was married to sculptor Carl Andre!
.
I loved this story. Xochitlâ€™s writing made this such an easy story to connect to as a first-generation daughter of immigrants, and at points I also found myself laughing out loud. I paired this book with what I would have as cafeteria food (chicken salad) since Raquelâ€™s advisor makes a comment about how sheâ€™s come a long way from the MoMa cafe.

I know it's only March 31, but Anita De Monte Laughs Last bt Xochitl Gonzalez is currently a top contender for my favorite book of the year. Definitely added to the list of all-time favorites. 

You are totally sucked into the world of Anita de Monte and also Raquel, who is still finding her place in the world. The entire story infuses so much depth into each character and feels as if you're getting fuller and fuller as you read. You want more and more, and the author does just that as you feel fire about Anita's story and anxiety for the choices Raquel is making. You are thoroughly disgusted and angry, not because you hate the book but because you are angry about the circumstances and want retribution right along with Anita. Gonzalez made the characters come alive and created a story that might be fictional but which is very much not a fictional story to so many voices. You end the book wanting to go out and find those who are forgotten and give them back their power, even in death. Readers will find themselves audibly responding to the story because it feels less like words on a page than a conversation and story you are hearing from a close friend.
